[1]
Date: Sat, 16 Jul 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE update, 15 Jul 2005 [edited]
<http://oie.int/downld/AVIAN%20INFLUENZA/Thailand%20Follow-up%20Report%
20No61.pdf>

The follow-up report No 61, dated 15 Jul 2005, sent to the OIE by Dr. Yukol
Limlamthong, Director-General, Department of Livestock Development, Bangkok,
includes -- among others -- the following data pertaining to 4 outbreaks of
Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza, recorded since 5 Jul 2005 in 4 different
farms in Supanburi Province, Muang district, Thailand.
Subdistrict/Start/Species/Susceptible/cases/deaths/destroyed/slaughtered
Tah Rahad/ 13 Jul 2005/ native chicken/40 /10 /10 /30 /-
Suan Tang/13 Jul 2005/ broiler/16 000 / 1638 / 1638 / 14 362/-
Rai Rot/ 13 Jul 2005 / native chicken / 114 / 45 / 45 /69 /-
Sala Khao/ 5 Jul 2005* / quail / 122 222 / 14 880 /14 880 /107 /120 /-
*Confirmed 14 Jul 2005
Description of affected population(s):
The native chickens were free-ranging type. The broiler and quail farms were
traditional practice [the management of which] to be improved for sufficient
biosecurity.
Laboratory where diagnosis was made: National Institute of Animal Health,
Department of Livestock Development.
Diagnostic tests used:
AGP, HA, Pathogen isolation by egg inoculation and ICPI
Source of outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Unknown or inconclusive
Control measures:
stamping out; quarantine; movement control inside the country; screening;
zoning; disinfection of infected premises/establishments.
Vaccination: prohibited.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
